    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-08-18T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-08-18T14:00:00-05:00" n="198"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.5048/4a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-08-18T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 18, 1928—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. The Department anticipates a repetition shortly by Buell<note n="25"
                        xml:id="d198fn25">Raymond Leslie Buell, author of <hi rend="italic">The
                            Native Problem in Africa</hi> (New York, 1928).</note> of his charges
                    concerning the Firestone concession and the American loan in the lectures he
                    plans delivering at the Williamstown Institute of Politics. The advisability of
                    preparing a statement in refutation, <pb facs="0360" n="250" xml:id="pg_250"/>
                    along the lines of the telegram Hines<note n="26" xml:id="d198fn26">W. D. Hines,
                        Firestone representative in Liberia.</note> recently sent Firestone, is, so
                    the Department understands, being discussed by Hines with President King. If the
                    latter should desire to issue a statement for distribution to the American press
                    on the subject, you should inform the President of Liberia that the Associated
                    Press is ready to handle his statement which should be sent by him as a direct
                    message to the Associated Press, with a request for appropriate publicity for
                    the statement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
